DURBAN - An uMlazi high school teacher was suspended after a video of her caning pupils went viral last week. On Monday morning, a high-level delegation from the Department of Education visited the school where the announcement was made. Pupils cheered when Dr Enoch Nzama, Head of Department at the education department, announced their decision to suspend the teacher. Nzama further warned teachers to remain calm and practice restraint when dealing with pupils. "Once the incident is caught on camera, it is shared to social media and goes viral," he warned. To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window. Watch: Dr Enoch Nzama, Head of Department at the education department addresses media after suspending a teacher for caning pupils He said they were disheartened at having to take such action against a teacher but the deparment was firm on their stance when it came to corporal punishment In a statement, Kwazi Mthethwa, spokesperson for the department, said they have a zero tolerance towards cases of corporal punishment. He added that an investigation will be launched at the school. The teacher is believed to be a history teacher who has taught at the school for more than 20 years. She is in her 60s. A second video of another teacher caning pupils also went viral on social media last week. Nzama could not confirm if the teacher or school in the second video was from the province. Daily News